*WARNING TO ALL RE CPU HEATSINK FANS*

We recently had a serious failure in our year-old file server where the CPU
acted erratically and wrote garbage on the drive. I traced this to:

1. The CPU fan was not powered;

2. The reason that it was not powered was that it was locked up;

3. There was about 1/32" between the fan top (the INLET for AIR) and the
    sheet metal bracket holding the drives!

Obviously, an idiot assembled this machine (which was a Taiwan clone). But I
learned some valuable things, notes below:

ALLOW AIR TO GO INTO THE FAN (like, at least 1/2"

I worked for a company that made high - power electronics, and we used a lot of
fans. Good fans use ball bearings; this fan (and I suspect all these heatsink
fans) was a sleeve bearing type. *These do not last* without TLC, folks.  In
fact, fans were specifically excluded from our warranty.  I freed the fan rotor
with Liquid Wrench, but the fan, being impedence-protected, destroyed its
electronics or internal wiring before causing a short from a locked-up rotor
and could not be brought back to life.  I examined several fans at local
computer stores, and there was no real quality difference between 11 dollar and
30 dollar fan/HS assemblies (not including thermoelectric devices, of course).

So, I would *Strongly Advise* that every three months or so, you should
disassemble the fan from the heatsink (carefully, the aluminum is soft), remove
the label covering up the shaft C-clip, and place *one drop* from the head of a
pin of Liquid Wrench or WD-40 on the shaft. Again, be careful in reassembly
(airflow should go in, this is always noted on the fan) and be careful not to
strip the aluminum of the heatsink.

When installing the heatsink, if you have the type that has fins going on only
one direction, the heatsink should be installed with the fins vertical to the
direction that the CPU will be sitting (if you have a desk model, this doesn't
matter).  It makes a small difference, and may buy you something should the fan
fail. Get it right: I would not advise trying to remove the heatsink 24 hours
after installation, or after 1 hour of operation. That glue is good, and you
might crack the CPU trying to remove it. MAKE SURE YOU HAVE ENOUGH CASE
CLERANCE FIRST!! before permanently installing the heatsink. YOU SHOULD WRITE
WHAT KIND OF CPU THE CHIP IS SOMEWHERE, as you are going to (more or less
permanently) cover the chip label.

Incidentally, our 486dx266 was not destroyed by this affair, but we
narrowly escaped disk disaster.  Remember that CPU failures won't cause parity
errors, and the CPU is doing millions of things a second even if you are
sitting at a prompt. JUST ONE MISTAKE by the CPU could be, as they say,
"bad"....



